{
  "answer": "**Iqbal does not name a specific individual historical figure as an exemplary ancestor in this chapter.** Instead, he refers collectively to the early Muslim/Arab forebears—the \"desert-dwellers\" from the \"cradle of camel-herders\"—who rose from poverty to create civilizations and rule the world, exemplified by the feat of crushing \"the crown upon the head of Darius\" (referring to the conquest of the Persian Empire).[^1]\n\nThese ancestors embody action, pride (\"Poverty is my pride\"), and imperial achievement, in contrast to the modern Muslim youth who are \"all talk\" and have lost their inheritance.[^1] The chapter closes with a metaphor invoking Jacob (peer-e-Kanaan), but this laments lost knowledge in Europe rather than praising an ancestor.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 13 \"Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam\" (translation), [p-365462](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/13-khitab-ba-jawanan-e-islam/translation/#p-365462).",
